# qa-7th vscode SEV-2 regression — bufferline overflow chevron clicks
# should actually scroll the strip. Before the fix, the
# auto-scroll-to-keep-active-tab-visible logic in ui::bufferline::draw
# immediately reset bufferline_first_visible after the chevron click.
#
# Fix: app.bufferline_active_at_scroll = app.active stamp; while it
# matches active, auto-scroll is suppressed. Verifies a single ‹ click
# actually shifts what's shown.

# Seed enough files to force overflow at the default 120-cell width.
write a.txt "1"
write b.txt "2"
write c.txt "3"
write d.txt "4"
write e.txt "5"
write f.txt "6"
write g.txt "7"
write h.txt "8"
open a.txt
open b.txt
open c.txt
open d.txt
open e.txt
open f.txt
open g.txt
open h.txt

# Close the file tree so the bufferline + its chevrons start at col 0.
command view.toggle_tree

# After 8 opens, the active tab is h.txt — bufferline is showing
# h.txt at the right edge with first_visible > 0. The ‹ chevron
# exists at col 0 of the bufferline row (row 1 in screen, 0-based).
expect screen contains "‹"

# Click the chevron repeatedly — each click decrements
# bufferline_first_visible by 1. With user_scroll_pinned stamped,
# the auto-scroll-to-keep-active-visible does NOT clobber the
# manual scroll. Walking all the way left should reveal a.txt
# even though h.txt is still active.
click 0 1
click 0 1
click 0 1
click 0 1
click 0 1
click 0 1
click 0 1

# a.txt should now be at the left edge of the strip — proves the
# chevron clicks weren't reverted by the auto-scroll.
expect screen contains "a.txt"
